    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Exploratory Sales Analysis\"\ndate: \"2025-03-15\"\ncategories: [Python, Data Analysis, EDA]\ndescription: \"Cleaning and exploring a retail dataset to surface seasonal trends and product performance using Pandas and Plotly.\"\npage-layout: full\ntoc: true\ncode-fold: true\n---\n\n```{=html}\n<div style=\"margin-bottom: 2rem;\">\n  <span class=\"pill pill-neon\">Python</span>\n  <span class=\"pill\">Pandas</span>\n  <span class=\"pill\">Plotly</span>\n  <span class=\"pill\">EDA</span>\n</div>\n```\n\n## Overview\n\nEvery retail business generates transaction logs — thousands of rows tracking what sold, when, and where. The problem is rarely a lack of data. It's knowing what to look at first.\n\nThis project takes a synthetic retail dataset and works through a structured EDA process: cleaning the data, understanding its shape, and then asking progressively sharper questions until a few genuinely useful patterns emerge.\n\n---\n\n## Dataset\n\nThe dataset used here is a synthetic retail sales log with the following columns: `date`, `product`, `category`, `region`, `units_sold`, and `revenue`. It covers 12 months of transactions across four product categories.\n\n---\n\n## Setup & Data Loading\n\n::: {#78a5fe0b .cell execution_count=1}\n``` {.python .cell-code}\nimport pandas as pd\nimport plotly.express as px\nimport plotly.graph_objects as go\nimport numpy as np\n\n# Reproducible synthetic dataset\nnp.random.seed(42)\n\ndates = pd.date_range(\"2024-01-01\", \"2024-12-31\", freq=\"D\")\ncategories = [\"Electronics\", \"Apparel\", \"Home & Garden\", \"Sports\"]\nregions = [\"Dublin\", \"Cork\", \"Galway\", \"Limerick\"]\n\nrows = []\nfor date in dates:\n    for _ in range(np.random.randint(3, 8)):\n        cat = np.random.choice(categories)\n        base = {\"Electronics\": 180, \"Apparel\": 55, \"Home & Garden\": 90, \"Sports\": 70}[cat]\n        seasonal = 1 + 0.3 * np.sin((date.month - 1) * np.pi / 6)\n        rows.append({\n            \"date\": date,\n            \"category\": cat,\n            \"region\": np.random.choice(regions),\n            \"units_sold\": int(np.random.poisson(seasonal * 5)),\n            \"revenue\": round(base * seasonal * np.random.uniform(0.85, 1.15) * np.random.poisson(seasonal * 5), 2)\n        })\n\ndf = pd.DataFrame(rows)\ndf[\"month\"] = df[\"date\"].dt.to_period(\"M\").astype(str)\ndf[\"month_num\"] = df[\"date\"].dt.month\n\nprint(f\"Rows: {len(df):,} | Columns: {df.shape[1]}\")\ndf.head()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}\n```\nRows: 1,883 | Columns: 7\n```\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1}\n```{=html}\n<div>\n<style scoped>\n    .dataframe tbody tr th:only-of-type {\n        vertical-align: middle;\n    }\n\n    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n        vertical-align: top;\n    }\n\n    .dataframe thead th {\n        text-align: right;\n    }\n</style>\n<table border=\"1\" class=\"dataframe\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr style=\"text-align: right;\">\n      <th></th>\n      <th>date</th>\n      <th>category</th>\n      <th>region</th>\n      <th>units_sold</th>\n      <th>revenue</th>\n      <th>month</th>\n      <th>month_num</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <th>0</th>\n      <td>2024-01-01</td>\n      <td>Electronics</td>\n      <td>Galway</td>\n      <td>4</td>\n      <td>998.87</td>\n      <td>2024-01</td>\n      <td>1</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>1</th>\n      <td>2024-01-01</td>\n      <td>Sports</td>\n      <td>Limerick</td>\n      <td>4</td>\n      <td>289.40</td>\n      <td>2024-01</td>\n      <td>1</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>2</th>\n      <td>2024-01-01</td>\n      <td>Home &amp; Garden</td>\n      <td>Limerick</td>\n      <td>4</td>\n      <td>469.54</td>\n      <td>2024-01</td>\n      <td>1</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>3</th>\n      <td>2024-01-01</td>\n      <td>Home &amp; Garden</td>\n      <td>Limerick</td>\n      <td>3</td>\n      <td>755.10</td>\n      <td>2024-01</td>\n      <td>1</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>4</th>\n      <td>2024-01-01</td>\n      <td>Sports</td>\n      <td>Galway</td>\n      <td>2</td>\n      <td>331.66</td>\n      <td>2024-01</td>\n      <td>1</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n\n---\n\n## Data Quality Check\n\nBefore anything else, check for nulls and confirm the data types are what you'd expect.\n\n::: {#93bd6a4d .cell execution_count=2}\n``` {.python .cell-code}\nprint(\"Null values:\\n\", df.isnull().sum())\nprint(\"\\nData types:\\n\", df.dtypes)\nprint(f\"\\nDate range: {df['date'].min().date()} → {df['date'].max().date()}\")\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}\n```\nNull values:\n date          0\ncategory      0\nregion        0\nunits_sold    0\nrevenue       0\nmonth         0\nmonth_num     0\ndtype: int64\n\nData types:\n date          datetime64[ns]\ncategory              object\nregion                object\nunits_sold             int64\nrevenue              float64\nmonth                 object\nmonth_num              int32\ndtype: object\n\nDate range: 2024-01-01 → 2024-12-31\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n\nNo nulls, correct types, full year of coverage. Clean enough to move straight into analysis.\n\n---\n\n## Monthly Revenue Trend\n\nThe first question: is revenue growing, declining, or seasonal?\n\n::: {#23dabaf4 .cell execution_count=3}\n``` {.python .cell-code}\nmonthly = df.groupby(\"month\")[\"revenue\"].sum().reset_index()\nmonthly.columns = [\"month\", \"total_revenue\"]\n\nfig = px.line(\n    monthly, x=\"month\", y=\"total_revenue\",\n    title=\"Monthly Revenue — Full Year\",\n    labels={\"month\": \"\", \"total_revenue\": \"Revenue (€)\"},\n    markers=True,\n    color_discrete_sequence=[\"#7fff6e\"]\n)\nfig.update_layout(\n    plot_bgcolor=\"#14141f\", paper_bgcolor=\"#14141f\",\n    font_color=\"#9898b0\", title_font_color=\"#ffffff\",\n    xaxis=dict(gridcolor=\"#252535\", tickangle=-30),\n    yaxis=dict(gridcolor=\"#252535\"),\n    hoverlabel=dict(bgcolor=\"#1a1a26\", font_color=\"#e2e2e2\")\n)\nfig.update_traces(line_width=2.5)\nfig.show()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div>            <script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/mathjax/2.7.5/MathJax.js?config=TeX-AMS-MML_SVG\"></script><script>if (window.MathJax && window.MathJax.Hub && window.MathJax.Hub.Config) {window.MathJax.Hub.Config({SVG: {font: \"STIX-Web\"}});}</script>                <script>window.PlotlyConfig = {MathJaxConfig: 'local'};</script>\n        <script charset=\"utf-8\" src=\"https://cdn.plot.ly/plotly-3.4.0.min.js\" integrity=\"sha256-KEmPoupLpFyGMyGAiOsiNDbKDKAvxXAn/W+oQa0ZAfk=\" crossorigin=\"anonymous\"></script>                <div id=\"39d639b2-8801-407e-a548-5c879564389d\" class=\"plotly-graph-div\" style=\"height:525px; width:100%;\"></div>            <script>                window.PLOTLYENV=window.PLOTLYENV || {};                                if (document.getElementById(\"39d639b2-8801-407e-a548-5c879564389d\")) {                    Plotly.newPlot(                        \"39d639b2-8801-407e-a548-5c879564389d\",                        [{\"hovertemplate\":\"=%{x}\\u003cbr\\u003eRevenue (\\u20ac)=%{y}\\u003cextra\\u003e\\u003c\\u002fextra\\u003e\",\"legendgroup\":\"\",\"line\":{\"color\":\"#7fff6e\",\"dash\":\"solid\",\"width\":2.5},\"marker\":{\"symbol\":\"circle\"},\"mode\":\"lines+markers\",\"name\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"v\",\"showlegend\":false,\"x\":[\"2024-01\",\"2024-02\",\"2024-03\",\"2024-04\",\"2024-05\",\"2024-06\",\"2024-07\",\"2024-08\",\"2024-09\",\"2024-10\",\"2024-11\",\"2024-12\"],\"xaxis\":\"x\",\"y\":{\"dtype\":\"f8\",\"bdata\":\"16NwPVL880CPwvUoyCf4QK5H4XpkkABBFa5H4RLA\\u002f0CkcD0KY8P8QKRwPQq7C\\u002flAAAAAAIxe9UAAAAAAeEruQArXo3DVyeRA16NwPfLH5EApXI\\u002fCrU7mQK5H4XpcsupA\"},\"yaxis\":\"y\",\"type\":\"scatter\"}],                        {\"template\":{\"data\":{\"histogram2dcontour\":[{\"type\":\"histogram2dcontour\",\"colorbar\":{\"outlinewidth\":0,\"t